---
// Shared "config file handling" note for package-based (.deb / .rpm) upgrades.
// Single source of truth for this guidance, rendered by LinuxUpgradeSteps,
// TrendzUpgradeSteps, and the CE-to-PE upgrade page. There is no "merge" option
// in the package managers; the recommended flow is to base off the new file and
// carry custom values over.
import { Aside } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';

interface Props {
	platform: 'ubuntu' | 'centos';
}

const { platform } = Astro.props;
const isUbuntu = platform === 'ubuntu';
---

<Aside type="note">
	{isUbuntu ? (
		<p>At the <code>dpkg</code> configuration-file prompt (<code>[Y/I/N/O/D/Z]</code>) there is no "merge" option.</p>
	) : (
		<p><code>rpm</code> does not prompt about configuration files: it keeps your current file and writes the new default alongside it as <code>.rpmnew</code>.</p>
	)}
	<p>
		The recommended approach is to use the new configuration file as the base and carry your custom values over from your previous one.{' '}
		{isUbuntu ? (
			<>Press <strong>Y</strong> to install the package maintainer's version (your previous file is kept as <code>.dpkg-old</code>), then copy your custom values from the <code>.dpkg-old</code> file into the new one before starting the service.</>
		) : (
			<>Copy your custom values into the <code>.rpmnew</code> file, then replace your current configuration file with it before starting the service.</>
		)}
	</p>
</Aside>
